 that fewer people will enter working- and military-age groups during 1959-65 than we had estimated.\n\nAbsence of Chinese Communists at bloc agricultural conference may have been caused by a desire to avoid criticism on communes.\n\nBloc sponsored military training program for Guinea appears to be under way.\n\nII. ASIA-AFRICA\n\nSudan, perturbed over limitations of US aid and World Bank \"stalling,\" says it will apply for Soviet aid.\n\nKhrushchev expected to offer substantial credits for Indian Third Five Year Plan.\n\nIII. THE WEST\n\nFrench cabinet changes show De Gaulle's determination to implement his Algerian policy.\n\nFidel Castro will probably accept Mikoyan's invitation to visit Moscow; resumption of diplomatic relations between USSR and Cuba also appears likely.\n\nCuba notifies UN of its candidacy for a seat on Security Council", "token_count": 137, "token_end_0based": 136, "token_start_0based": 0, "token_text": "6 february 1960 i the communist bloc soviet census reveals that fewer people will enter working and military-age groups during 1959-65 than we had estimated absence of chinese communists at bloc agricultural conference may have been caused by a desire to avoid criticism on communes bloc sponsored military training program for guinea appears to be under way ii asia-africa sudan perturbed over limitations of us aid and world bank stalling says it will apply for soviet aid khrushchev expected to offer substantial credits for indian third five year plan iii the west french cabinet changes show de gaulle's determination to implement his algerian policy fidel castro will probably accept mikoyan's invitation to visit moscow resumption of diplomatic relations between ussr and cuba also appears likely cuba notifies un of its candidacy for a seat on security council", "unred_source_page": 3}
